  <data key="d14">ann.concept-charity-has-object-concept-god-st-ii-ii-q025-a001-resp | ann.concept-charity-has-object-concept-god-st-ii-ii-q026-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q025.a001.resp | st.ii-ii.q026.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">, since what we ought to love in our neighbor is that he may be in God . Hence it is clear that it is specifically the same act whereby we love God , and whereby we love our neighbor. Consequently the habit of charity extends not only to the love of God , but also to the love of our neighbor. | h consists essentially in God , as the First Principle, whence it flows to all who are capable of happiness . Therefore God ought to be loved chiefly and before all out of charity : for He is loved as the cause of happiness , whereas our neighbor is loved as receiving together with us a share of happiness from Him.</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.charity" target="concept.neighbor" id="edge.concept.charity.has_object.concept.neighbor">
