  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q008" target="st.ii-ii.q008.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q008.contains.st.ii-ii.q008.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q008.contains.st.ii-ii.q008.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q008</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.8 — The gift of understanding</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q008.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.8 a.4 — Do all who are in a state of grace have the gift of understanding?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q008.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">In all who are in a state of grace , there must needs be rectitude of the will , since grace prepares man's will for good , according to Augustine (Contra Julian. Pelag. iv, 3). Now the will cannot be rightly directed to</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q008" target="st.ii-ii.q008.a005" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q008.contains.st.ii-ii.q008.a005">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q008.contains.st.ii-ii.q008.a005</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q008</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.8 — The gift of understanding</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q008.a005</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.8 a.5 — Is this gift to be found in those who are without grace?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q008.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">As stated above ( I-II:68:1 ; I-II:68:2 ) the gifts of the Holy Ghost perfect the soul , according as it is amenable to the motion of the Holy Ghost . Accordingly then, the intellectual light of grace is called the gift </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q008" target="st.ii-ii.q008.a006" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q008.contains.st.ii-ii.q008.a006">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q008.contains.st.ii-ii.q008.a006</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q008</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.8 — The gift of understanding</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q008.a006</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.8 a.6 — The relationship of the gift of understanding to the other gifts</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q008.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">The difference between the gift of understanding and three of the others, viz. piety, fortitude , and fear, is evident, since the gift of understanding belongs to the cognitive power, while the three belong to the appeti</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q008" target="st.ii-ii.q008.a007" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q008.contains.st.ii-ii.q008.a007">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q008.contains.st.ii-ii.q008.a007</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q008</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.8 — The gift of understanding</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q008.a007</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.8 a.7 — Which of the beatitudes corresponds to this gift?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q008.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">Two things are contained in the sixth beatitude, as also in the others, one by way of merit , viz. cleanness of heart; the other by way of reward, viz. the sight of God , as stated above ( I-II:69:2 ; I-II:69:4 ), and ea</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q008" target="st.ii-ii.q008.a008" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q008.contains.st.ii-ii.q008.a008">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q008.contains.st.ii-ii.q008.a008</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q008</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.8 — The gift of understanding</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q008.a008</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.8 a.8 — Which of the fruits?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q008.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">The fruits of the Spirit , as stated above ( I-II:70:1 ), when we were discussing them, are so called because they are something ultimate and delightful, produced in us by the power of the Holy Ghost . Now the ultimate a</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q009" target="concept.faith" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q009.treated_in.concept.faith">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q009.treated_in.concept.faith</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q009</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.9 — The gift of knowledge</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.faith</data>
  <data key="d12">Faith</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q009-treated-in-concept-faith-st-ii-ii-q009-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q009.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">on it. Accordingly, two things are requisite in order that the human intellect may perfectly assent to the truth of the faith : one of these is that he should have a sound grasp of the things that are proposed to be believed , and this pertains to the gift of understanding, as stated</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q009" target="concept.knowledge_gift" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q009.treated_in.concept.knowledge_gift">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q009.treated_in.concept.knowledge_gift</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q009</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.9 — The gift of knowledge</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.knowledge_gift</data>
  <data key="d12">Gift of Knowledge</data>
  <data key="d13">gift_holy_spirit</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q009-treated-in-concept-knowledge-gift-st-ii-ii-q009-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q009.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">nd right judgment on them, so as to discern what is to be believed , from what is not to be believed , and for this the gift of knowledge is required.</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q009" target="st.ii-ii.q009.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q009.contains.st.ii-ii.q009.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q009.contains.st.ii-ii.q009.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q009</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.9 — The gift of knowledge</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q009.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.9 a.1 — Is knowledge a gift?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q009.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">Grace is more perfect than nature , and, therefore, does not fail in those things wherein man can be perfected by nature . Now, when a man, by his natural reason , assents by his intellect to some truth , he is perfected</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q009" target="st.ii-ii.q009.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q009.contains.st.ii-ii.q009.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q009.contains.st.ii-ii.q009.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q009</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.9 — The gift of knowledge</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q009.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.9 a.2 — Is it about Divine things?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q009.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">A sure judgment about a thing is formed chiefly from its cause , and so the order of judgments should be according to the order of causes . For just as the first cause is the cause of the second, so ought the judgment ab</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q009" target="st.ii-ii.q009.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q009.contains.st.ii-ii.q009.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q009.contains.st.ii-ii.q009.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q009</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.9 — The gift of knowledge</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q009.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.9 a.3 — Is it speculative or practical?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q009.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">As stated above ( II-II:9:8 ), the gift of knowledge , like the gift of understanding, is ordained to the certitude of faith . Now faith consists primarily and principally in speculation, in as much as it is founded on t</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q009" target="st.ii-ii.q009.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q009.contains.st.ii-ii.q009.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q009.contains.st.ii-ii.q009.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q009</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.9 — The gift of knowledge</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q009.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.9 a.4 — Which beatitude corresponds to it?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q009.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">Right judgment about creatures belongs properly to knowledge . Now it is through creatures that man's aversion from God is occasioned, according to Wisdom 14:11 : "Creatures . . . are turned to an abomination . . . and a</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q010" target="concept.faith" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q010.treated_in.concept.faith">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q010.treated_in.concept.faith</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q010</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.10 — Unbelief in general</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.faith</data>
  <data key="d12">Faith</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q010-treated-in-concept-faith-st-ii-ii-q010-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q010.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">taken in two ways: first, by way of pure negation, so that a man be called an unbeliever, merely because he has not the faith . Secondly, unbelief may be taken by way of opposition to the faith ; in which sense a man refuses to hear the faith , or despises it, according to Isaiah 53:1</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q010" target="concept.unbelief" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q010.treated_in.concept.unbelief">
