  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q024.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">Since, as stated in I:80:2 , the appetite is twofold, namely the sensitive, and the intellective which is called the will , the object of each is the good , but in different ways: for the object of the sensitive appetite</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q024" target="st.ii-ii.q024.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q024.contains.st.ii-ii.q024.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q024.contains.st.ii-ii.q024.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q024</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.24 — The subject of charity</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q024.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.24 a.2 — Is charity caused in man by preceding acts or by a Divine infusion?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q024.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">As stated above ( II-II:23:1 ), charity is a friendship of man for God , founded upon the fellowship of everlasting happiness . Now this fellowship is in respect, not of natural , but of gratuitous gifts , for, according</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q024" target="st.ii-ii.q024.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q024.contains.st.ii-ii.q024.a003">
