  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q024.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.24 a.4 — Does it increase in the person who has it?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q024.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">The charity of a wayfarer can increase. For we are called wayfarers by reason of our being on the way to God , Who is the last end of our happiness . On this way we advance as we get nigh to God , Who is approached, "not</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q024" target="st.ii-ii.q024.a005" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q024.contains.st.ii-ii.q024.a005">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q024.contains.st.ii-ii.q024.a005</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q024</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.24 — The subject of charity</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q024.a005</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.24 a.5 — Does it increase by addition?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q024.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">Every addition is of something to something else: so that in every addition we must at least presuppose that the things added together are distinct before the addition. Consequently if charity be added to charity , the a</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q024" target="st.ii-ii.q024.a006" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q024.contains.st.ii-ii.q024.a006">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q024.contains.st.ii-ii.q024.a006</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q024</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.24 — The subject of charity</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q024.a006</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.24 a.6 — Does it increase by every act?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q024.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">The spiritual increase of charity is somewhat like the increase of a body. Now bodily increase in animals and plants is not a continuous movement, so that, to wit, if a thing increase so much in so much time, it need to </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q024" target="st.ii-ii.q024.a007" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q024.contains.st.ii-ii.q024.a007">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q024.contains.st.ii-ii.q024.a007</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q024</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.24 — The subject of charity</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q024.a007</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.24 a.7 — Does it increase indefinitely?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q024.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">A term to the increase of a form may be fixed in three ways: first by reason of the form itself having a fixed measure, and when this has been reached it is no longer possible to go any further in that form, but if any f</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q024" target="st.ii-ii.q024.a008" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q024.contains.st.ii-ii.q024.a008">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q024.contains.st.ii-ii.q024.a008</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q024</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.24 — The subject of charity</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q024.a008</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.24 a.8 — Can the charity of a wayfarer be perfect?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q024.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">The perfection of charity may be understood in two ways: first with regard to the object loved, secondly with regard to the person who loves. With regard to the object loved, charity is perfect, if the object be loved as</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q024" target="st.ii-ii.q024.a009" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q024.contains.st.ii-ii.q024.a009">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q024.contains.st.ii-ii.q024.a009</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q024</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.24 — The subject of charity</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q024.a009</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.24 a.9 — The various degrees of charity</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q024.a009.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">The spiritual increase of charity may be considered in respect of a certain likeness to the growth of the human body. For although this latter growth may be divided into many parts, yet it has certain fixed divisions acc</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q024" target="st.ii-ii.q024.a010" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q024.contains.st.ii-ii.q024.a010">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q024.contains.st.ii-ii.q024.a010</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q024</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.24 — The subject of charity</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q024.a010</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.24 a.10 — Can charity diminish?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q024.a010.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">The quantity which charity has in comparison with its proper object, cannot decrease, even as neither can it increase, as stated above ( Article 4, Reply to Objection 2 ). Since, however, it increases in that quantity wh</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q024" target="st.ii-ii.q024.a011" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q024.contains.st.ii-ii.q024.a011">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q024.contains.st.ii-ii.q024.a011</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q024</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.24 — The subject of charity</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q024.a011</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.24 a.11 — Can charity be lost after it has been possessed?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q024.a011.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">The Holy Ghost dwells in us by charity , as shown above ( Article 2 ; Q 23,24 ). We can, accordingly, consider charity in three ways: first on the part of the Holy Ghost , Who moves the soul to love God , and in this res</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q024" target="st.ii-ii.q024.a012" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q024.contains.st.ii-ii.q024.a012">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q024.contains.st.ii-ii.q024.a012</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q024</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.24 — The subject of charity</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q024.a012</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.24 a.12 — Is it lost through one mortal sin?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q024.a012.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">That one contrary is removed by the other contrary supervening. Now every mortal sin is contrary to charity by its very nature , which consists in man's loving God above all things, and subjecting himself to Him entirely</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q025" target="concept.charity" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q025.treated_in.concept.charity">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q025.treated_in.concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q025</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.25 — The object of charity</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d12">Charity</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q025-treated-in-concept-charity-st-ii-ii-q025-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q025.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">that it is specifically the same act whereby we love God , and whereby we love our neighbor. Consequently the habit of charity extends not only to the love of God , but also to the love of our neighbor.</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q025" target="concept.god" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q025.treated_in.concept.god">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q025.treated_in.concept.god</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q025</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.25 — The object of charity</data>
