  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q032</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.32 — Almsdeeds</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.mercy</data>
  <data key="d12">Mercy</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q032-treated-in-concept-mercy-st-ii-ii-q032-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q032.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">s being "a deed whereby something is given to the needy, out of compassion and for God's sake," which motive belongs to mercy, as stated above ( II-II:30:2 ). Hence it is clear that almsgiving is, properly speaking, an act of mercy. This appears in its very name, for in Greek eleemosy</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q032" target="st.ii-ii.q032.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q032.contains.st.ii-ii.q032.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q032.contains.st.ii-ii.q032.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q032</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.32 — Almsdeeds</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q032.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.32 a.1 — Is almsgiving an act of charity?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q032.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">External acts belong to that virtue which regards the motive for doing those acts. Now the motive for giving alms is to relieve one who is in need. Wherefore some have defined alms as being "a deed whereby something is g</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q032" target="st.ii-ii.q032.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q032.contains.st.ii-ii.q032.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q032.contains.st.ii-ii.q032.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q032</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.32 — Almsdeeds</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q032.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.32 a.2 — The different kinds of alms</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q032.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">The aforesaid distinction of almsdeeds is suitably taken from the various needs of our neighbor: some of which affect the soul , and are relieved by spiritual almsdeeds , while others affect the body, and are relieved by</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q032" target="st.ii-ii.q032.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q032.contains.st.ii-ii.q032.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q032.contains.st.ii-ii.q032.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q032</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.32 — Almsdeeds</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q032.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.32 a.3 — Which alms are of greater account, spiritual or corporal?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q032.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">There are two ways of comparing these almsdeeds. First, simply; and in this respect, spiritual almsdeeds hold the first place, for three reasons. First, because the offering is more excellent, since it is a spiritual gif</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q032" target="st.ii-ii.q032.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q032.contains.st.ii-ii.q032.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q032.contains.st.ii-ii.q032.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q032</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.32 — Almsdeeds</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q032.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.32 a.4 — Do corporal alms have a spiritual effect?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q032.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">Corporal almsdeeds may be considered in three ways. First, with regard to their substance , and in this way they have merely a corporal effect, inasmuch as they supply our neighbor's corporal needs. Secondly, they may be</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q032" target="st.ii-ii.q032.a005" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q032.contains.st.ii-ii.q032.a005">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q032.contains.st.ii-ii.q032.a005</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q032</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.32 — Almsdeeds</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q032.a005</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.32 a.5 — Is the giving of alms a matter of precept?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q032.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">As love of our neighbor is a matter of precept, whatever is a necessary condition to the love of our neighbor is a matter of precept also. Now the love of our neighbor requires that not only should we be our neighbor's w</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q032" target="st.ii-ii.q032.a006" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q032.contains.st.ii-ii.q032.a006">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q032.contains.st.ii-ii.q032.a006</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q032</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.32 — Almsdeeds</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q032.a006</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.32 a.6 — Should corporal alms be given out of the things we need?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q032.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">A thing is necessary in two ways: first, because without it something is impossible, and it is altogether wrong to give alms out of what is necessary to us in this sense; for instance, if a man found himself in the prese</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q032" target="st.ii-ii.q032.a007" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q032.contains.st.ii-ii.q032.a007">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q032.contains.st.ii-ii.q032.a007</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q032</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.32 — Almsdeeds</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q032.a007</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.32 a.7 — Should corporal alms be given out of ill-gotten goods?</data>
