  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q044</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.44 — The precepts of charity</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q044.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.44 a.3 — Do two suffice?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q044.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">Charity , as stated above ( II-II:23:1 ), is a kind of friendship. Now friendship is between one person and another, wherefore Gregory says (Hom. in Ev. xvii): " Charity is not possible between less than two": and it has</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q044" target="st.ii-ii.q044.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q044.contains.st.ii-ii.q044.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q044.contains.st.ii-ii.q044.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q044</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.44 — The precepts of charity</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q044.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.44 a.4 — Is it fittingly prescribed that we should love God, "with thy whole heart"?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q044.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">Since precepts are given about acts of virtue , an act is a matter of precept according as it is an act of virtue . Now it is requisite for an act of virtue that not only should it fall on its own matter , but also that </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q044" target="st.ii-ii.q044.a005" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q044.contains.st.ii-ii.q044.a005">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q044.contains.st.ii-ii.q044.a005</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q044</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.44 — The precepts of charity</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q044.a005</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.44 a.5 — Is it fittingly added: "With thy whole mind," etc.?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q044.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">This precept is differently worded in various places: for, as we said in the first objection, in Deuteronomy 6 three points are mentioned: "with thy whole heart," and "with thy whole soul ," and "with thy whole strength.</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q044" target="st.ii-ii.q044.a006" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q044.contains.st.ii-ii.q044.a006">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q044.contains.st.ii-ii.q044.a006</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q044</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.44 — The precepts of charity</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q044.a006</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.44 a.6 — Is it possible to fulfil this precept in this life?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q044.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">A precept can be fulfilled in two ways; perfectly, and imperfectly. A precept is fulfilled perfectly, when the end intended by the author of the precept is reached; yet it is fulfilled, imperfectly however, when although</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q044" target="st.ii-ii.q044.a007" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q044.contains.st.ii-ii.q044.a007">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q044.contains.st.ii-ii.q044.a007</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q044</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.44 — The precepts of charity</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q044.a007</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.44 a.7 — The precept: "Thou shalt love thy neighbor as thyself"</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q044.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">This precept is fittingly expressed, for it indicates both the reason for loving and the mode of love. The reason for loving is indicated in the word "neighbor," because the reason why we ought to love others out of char</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q044" target="st.ii-ii.q044.a008" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q044.contains.st.ii-ii.q044.a008">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q044.contains.st.ii-ii.q044.a008</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q044</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.44 — The precepts of charity</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q044.a008</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.44 a.8 — Is the order of charity included in the precept?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q044.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">As stated above ( Article 4, Reply to Objection 1 ), the mode which is essential to an act of virtue comes under the precept which prescribes that virtuous act. Now the order of charity is essential to the virtue , since</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
