  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q023.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Accordingly, since there is a communication between man and God , inasmuch as He communicates His happiness to us, some kind of friendship must needs be based on this same communication, of which it is written ( 1 Corinthians 1:9 ): " God is faithful: by Whom you are called unto the fellowship of His Son." The love which is based on this communication, is charity : wherefore it is evident that charity is the friendship of man for God .</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q023.a001" target="concept.friendship_with_god" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a001.treated_in.concept.friendship_with_god">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a001.treated_in.concept.friendship_with_god</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q023.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.23 a.1 — Is charity friendship?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.friendship_with_god</data>
  <data key="d12">Friendship with God</data>
  <data key="d13">doctrine</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q023-a001-treated-in-concept-friendship-with-god-st-ii-ii-q023-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q023.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Accordingly, since there is a communication between man and God , inasmuch as He communicates His happiness to us, some kind of friendship must needs be based on this same communication, of which it is written ( 1 Corinthians 1:9 ): " God is faithful: by Whom you are called unto the fellowship of His Son." The love which is based on this communication, is charity : wherefore it is evident that charity is the friendship of man for God .</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q023.a002" target="concept.charity" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a002.treated_in.concept.charity">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a002.treated_in.concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q023.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.23 a.2 — Is it something created in the soul?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d12">Charity</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q023-a002-treated-in-concept-charity-st-ii-ii-q023-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q023.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">The Master looks thoroughly into this question in 17 of the First Book, and concludes that charity is not something created in the soul , but is the Holy Ghost Himself dwelling in the mind</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q023.a003" target="concept.charity" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a003.treated_in.concept.charity">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a003.treated_in.concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q023.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.23 a.3 — Is it a virtue?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d12">Charity</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q023-a003-treated-in-concept-charity-st-ii-ii-q023-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q023.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Wherefore, it follows that charity is a virtue , for, since charity attains God , it unites us to God , as evidenced by the authority of Augustine quoted above.</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q023.a003" target="concept.virtue" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a003.treated_in.concept.virtue">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a003.treated_in.concept.virtue</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q023.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.23 a.3 — Is it a virtue?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.virtue</data>
  <data key="d12">Virtue</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q023-a003-treated-in-concept-virtue-st-ii-ii-q023-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q023.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Wherefore human virtue which is the principle of all man's good acts consists in following the rule of human acts , which is twofold, as stated above ( II-II:17:1 ), viz</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q023.a004" target="concept.charity" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a004.treated_in.concept.charity">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a004.treated_in.concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q023.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.23 a.4 — Is it a special virtue?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d12">Charity</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q023-a004-treated-in-concept-charity-st-ii-ii-q023-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q023.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">But the Divine good , inasmuch as it is the object of happiness , has a special aspect of good , wherefore the love of charity , which is the love of that good , is a special kind of love</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q023.a005" target="concept.charity" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a005.treated_in.concept.charity">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a005.treated_in.concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q023.a005</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.23 a.5 — Is it one virtue?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d12">Charity</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q023-a005-treated-in-concept-charity-st-ii-ii-q023-a005-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q023.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Charity , as stated above ( Article 1 ) is a kind of friendship of man for God</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q023.a006" target="concept.charity" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a006.treated_in.concept.charity">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a006.treated_in.concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q023.a006</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.23 a.6 — Is it the greatest of the virtues?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d12">Charity</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q023-a006-treated-in-concept-charity-st-ii-ii-q023-a006-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q023.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">But faith and hope attain God indeed in so far as we derive from Him the knowledge of truth or the acquisition of good , whereas charity attains God Himself that it may rest in Him, but not that something may accrue to us from Him</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q023.a007" target="concept.charity" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a007.treated_in.concept.charity">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a007.treated_in.concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q023.a007</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.23 a.7 — Is any true virtue possible without it?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d12">Charity</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q023-a007-treated-in-concept-charity-st-ii-ii-q023-a007-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q023.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">The ultimate and principal good of man is the enjoyment of God , according to Psalm 72:28 : "It is good for me to adhere to God ," and to this good man is ordered by charity</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q023.a008" target="concept.charity" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a008.treated_in.concept.charity">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a008.treated_in.concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q023.a008</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.23 a.8 — Is it the form of the virtues?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.charity</data>
  <data key="d12">Charity</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q023-a008-treated-in-concept-charity-st-ii-ii-q023-a008-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q023.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Now it is evident, in accordance with what has been said ( Article 7 ), that it is charity which directs the acts of all other virtues to the last end, and which, consequently, also gives the form to all other acts of virtue : and it is precisely in this sense that charity is called the form of the virtues , for these are called virtues in relation to "informed" acts.</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q023.a008" target="concept.form_of_virtues" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a008.treated_in.concept.form_of_virtues">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a008.treated_in.concept.form_of_virtues</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q023.a008</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.23 a.8 — Is it the form of the virtues?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.form_of_virtues</data>
  <data key="d12">Form of the Virtues</data>
  <data key="d13">doctrine</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q023-a008-treated-in-concept-form-of-virtues-st-ii-ii-q023-a008-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q023.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Now it is evident, in accordance with what has been said ( Article 7 ), that it is charity which directs the acts of all other virtues to the last end, and which, consequently, also gives the form to all other acts of virtue : and it is precisely in this sense that charity is called the form of the virtues , for these are called virtues in relation to "informed" acts.</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q023.a008" target="concept.virtue" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q023.a008.treated_in.concept.virtue">
